<li id="cite_note-24"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-24">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://mises.org/rothbard/AGD/chapter10.asp">"1931—"The Tragic Year""</a>. Ludwig von Mises Institute<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://mises.org/rothbard/AGD/chapter10.asp">http://mises.org/rothbard/AGD/chapter10.asp</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved December 24, 2011</span>. "Throughout the European crisis, the Federal Reserve, particularly the New York Bank, tried its best to aid the European governments and to prop up unsound credit positions. ... The New York Federal Reserve loaned, in 1931, $125 million to the Bank of England, $25 million to the German Reichsbank, and smaller amounts to Hungary and Austria. As a result, much frozen assets were shifted, to become burdens to the United States."</span></span></li>
